        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Sept. 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi></date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have now read your paper, &amp; I hope that you will not think me presumptuous in writing another line to say how excellent it seems to me.— I believe that you have largely solved the problem of the affinities of the inhabitants of this most interesting little island, &amp; this is a delightful triumph.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Dear Sir Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9686.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">F. B. White 1878</ref> (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD’s annotated copy of White’s ‘Contributions to a knowledge of the hemipterous fauna of St. Helena, and speculations on its origin’ (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9686.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">F. B. White 1878</ref>), in the <hi rend="italic">Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London</hi>, is in the unbound journal collection in the Darwin Archive–CUL. White argued that fauna colonised the extremely isolated Atlantic island of St Helena from the north along a now submerged chain of island ‘stepping stones’, taking advantage of ocean currents and winds that had since then reversed direction owing to the end of a glacial period (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9686.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">F. B. White 1878</ref>, pp. 454–5).</note>
        </div>
    
